            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Director Luchina Fisher remembers the awards dinner of last year’s Athena Film Festival like it was yesterday. Surrounded by figures like Greta Gerwig, BC ’06; Gloria Steinem; and Beanie Feldstein, Fisher recalls the mesmerizing, powerful ambiance of the room."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“I was just sitting at the table with … powerful women who were from the industry, and just pinching myself because there’s a feeling of comfort and ease and power in being amongst these women and female-identified filmmakers,” Fisher, who directed the feature film “<a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/arts-and-entertainment/2021/03/11/director-luchina-fisher-presents-the-resilience-and-joyfulness-of-a-black-transgender-woman-in-mama-gloria/\">Mama Gloria</a>,” said. “It was just so nurturing and inspiring, and you don't get that at every festival, where you just feel so comfortable, like you’re just with your people.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "This year, however, there are no receptions, no live screenings, and no in-person panels—the 11th annual Athena Film Festival is completely virtual. Instead of a weekend packed with dozens of films and events, the festival has been spread out across the entire month of March, with films accessible to watch at any time within their scheduled weeks."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Yet, as Fisher notes, the goal of the festival remains the same: to celebrate the achievements of women filmmakers and to give them a platform to share their stories and work."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“I love that this film festival is really about heroic women or women who are making a difference in our world, that that’s what these films represent,” Fisher said. “I can’t think of a more perfect place for the New York premiere than Athena.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "With the uncertainties of the pandemic, festival organizers struggled to find the best way to capture the same welcoming and awe-inspiring dynamic that Fisher remembered. According to Kory Louko, BC ’17 and postbaccalaureate fellow for the Athena Film Festival, organizers had developed an in-person festival plan, a hybrid plan, and a fully virtual plan; it was not until September that the festival made the executive decision to go completely virtual."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“It was really a struggle working over the summer, because not only is everything changing around you and you don’t really know week to week what your job is going to look like, you’re also kind of doing twice or triple the work to try to plan for these different contingencies,” Louko said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The decision to move all film screenings and events online came after several other notable festivals, such as Sundance and South by Southwest, organized programming in fully virtual formats. Athena organizers attended virtual panels hosted by organizations such as FilmEx Film Festival Alliance, which has helped the Athena Film Festival address problems related to accessibility, curation, and sponsorship in a virtual environment."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "However, for many filmmakers showcasing films at the Festival this year, the virtual festival run has created a divide between the creators and the viewers, a relationship that fosters conversation and community. Fisher was supposed to premiere “Mama Gloria” in Chicago, the home of the the titular Gloria Allen, a Black transgender woman who founded a school that taught young women social graces for homeless transgender youth in Chicago."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“So many people [in Chicago] know her—her family is there, support is there, it would have been amazing to be on stage talking about the film—and I missed that gathering to watch films together and experience it with a crowd of people,” Fisher said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Director Rachel Fleit, whose short film “Ava & Bianca” follows the lives of two transgender women filmmakers, also shares this sentiment, especially given that she completed much of the editing for her film remotely."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“I think actually as a filmmaker, you kind of want to be able to sit in the audience while people are watching your movie on a big screen. It’s like the best feeling ever,” Fleit said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "For Miranda Winters and Rocky Romano, who co-directed the short film “We Can’t Breathe” about a female activist in response to the Black Lives Matter protests last summer, the virtual season has restricted them from seeing the reactions of viewers, many of whom were likely involved with the protests in some way. While the directors acknowledge that virtual film festivals have been crucial to telling such pressing stories about the work of female activists, they still miss the experience of seeing their film displayed on big screens, for viewers who may walk away from the film with a greater understanding of the protests and the Black Lives Matter movement."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“To take the film festival experience away from the filmmaker is like ripping the heart out of the filmmaker,” Romano said. “Everyone’s been doing a great job overcoming this and doing it virtually, but when you work really hard on a film and a project, there’s not a lot of accolades and pats on the back. Really, film festivals are where you get that chance, and all your suffering and passion gets a small little moment of glory and [being] highlighted and just the interaction.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The entirety of “We Can’t Breathe,” which lasts for eight minutes and 46 seconds, was filmed during the COVID-19 pandemic, with much of the footage taken by the film’s producer Rayna Zemel. According to Romano, the film includes footage from 50 to 60 days of the summer’s Black Lives Matter protests, taken on both professional video equipment and cellphones. This in-person filming posed challenges for the team: On top of fears of COVID-19 transmission, many protestors were concerned about being filmed."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "With a full filming and editing process of just a few months, the team had to create a final product that captured the complexities of the summer’s protests. Despite the lack of in-person film festivals, the team remarked that viewers at Athena and similar film festivals can still join in solidarity with others in dismantling systems of oppression."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“What I find fascinating about film is for eight minutes to an hour and a half, you actually shut up and listen; you can’t really talk back to the TV, so it’s an opportunity to really share something with somebody without them thinking about an answer or reply, where they actually sit back and actually absorb,” Romano said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Yoruba Richen, who directed the feature “How It Feels to Be Free,” noted that some of her filming had to adapt to pandemic safety protocols, with interviews filmed remotely on Zoom and a virtual editing process. The film, which includes Alicia Keys among its executive producers, follows the art and activism of six Black female performers—Lena Horne, Abbey Lincoln, Diahann Carroll, Nina Simone, Cicely Tyson, and Pam Grier."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Though Richen acknowledged that virtual film festivals have allowed for larger audiences than in-person ones, she also lamented that the team missed out on having the film shown more widely over the past few months, given that the industry’s production halt hindered her from selling the film."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Of course, we lose the networking, the in-person networking, just also watching a film together and that energy that you have in the room—those are some of my best experiences of watching films,” Richen said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "For directors showcasing their films at Athena from outside of the country, COVID-19 has made the film season much more difficult and confusing. Leonor Zúniga, the Nicaraguan director behind the film “Exiled,” has had to deal with this confusion abroad, as well as backlash from her home country."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Exiled” explores the life of Zoilamérica Ortega Murillo, the adopted daughter of the President of Nicaragua Daniel Ortega, who has publicly accused Ortega of rape. Zúniga created the entire film in secret and, afraid that the government would find out about the film, could not apply for funding. She fled Nicaragua and settled in Costa Rica, where she plans to remain until democracy is installed in her home country."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Zúniga has shown her film virtually in London and in the United States, where she has received glowing reviews. Yet she had not been able to share it at movie theaters in Nicaragua, though she said that she will soon share the film for one month in Nicaragua to show residents the truth about Ortega’s past, even at the risk of upsetting supporters of the government."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Though many filmmakers experienced isolation from viewers at virtual festivals, Zúniga felt that the pandemic and virtual film screenings actually allowed her and her viewers to feel less lonely and to become more educated about the Nicaraguan political crisis."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Before the pandemic, my country has been dealing with the most difficult crisis that we have had in the last 30 years, that forced a lot of people like us to leave our country,” Zúniga said. “I felt really lonely because the world continued moving and just a few people paid attention to what is happening in Nicaragua. So in a way, when the pandemic happened and a lot of people were affected by it, I feel less lonely.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "In order to help bridge the spatial gaps between directors and viewers, the Athena Film Festival has created a Discord channel, where everyone can discuss the films featured in the festival and ask questions of filmmakers and panelists to continue conversations inspired by the films."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "To encourage accessibility, the Athena Film Festival offers a special section on its website for films with closed captioning, panels with closed captioning, and pre-recorded Q&As and panels. Anyone in the United States with internet access can participate in viewings and panels, and films and shorts programs each cost $12."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "According to Louko, the film industry “has been incredibly behind” on handling issues of accessibility in film festivals. Many film festivals charge incredibly high prices for admission, and transportation to many of these festivals can cost just as much as the price to see the films. For people with a disability, seeing the screen or navigating the space poses additional challenges."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "To address issues of accessibility, the Festival is hosting a panel called “Disability Access and Visibility in Film and Television,” as well as featuring a shorts program called “Nothing About Us Without Us,” which dissects the visibility and representation of women and people with disabilities in film."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“I think it’s kind of two things. ... It’s partially because we’re going online that we’re able to do a lot of these things, and we’re thinking about a lot of these things, but it’s also ... because there are incredible disabled activists out there pushing people to be doing these things,” Louko said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Fleit, whose film is included in “Nothing About Us Without Us,” believes that having the ability to see films in one’s living room does have its advantages, especially when viewers can select what they want to see and when to see it, as opposed to buying a pass for a weekend event."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“I like the idea of the more broad approach, where you get to just see a movie that you’re really interested in seeing from the comfort of your living room, and you get to pause it and go and have a snack,” Fleit said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Dorothy Allen-Pickard, director of “Material Bodies,” a film focused on the relationship between amputees and their limbs, highlighted recent efforts to challenge ableism in film, both on-screen and behind the camera. Although she noted that the Athena Film Festival takes a social and political approach to its programming, she also cautioned that, especially in a virtual setting, film festivals with narrow focuses can bias towards certain audiences, therefore, limiting the work the focused programming can do."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“On the one hand, it can offer visibility if you’re in a program with, for example, other women filmmakers or films that are also about disability. And then, on the other hand, actually you limit the scope of the audience who are then going to go to watch those films,” Allen-Pickard said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "For Yuan Yuan, a Master of Fine Arts candidate at the New York University Tisch School of the Arts and the director of “Heading South,” virtual film festivals allow for greater visibility for women and filmmakers of color. Yuan and her peers have also been able to attend online workshops to improve writing and filmmaking skills. However, she still has reservations about the overall connectedness of virtual festivals."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“I think it’s easier to ask questions as well [at] all those panels, but I feel, one thing is about all those other panelists with this online, it’s really hard to know if you really have a relationship with that person,” Yuan said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Although audiences are spread out across the country, Kate Hackett, who directed the short film “Oleander,” feels as though the increased accessibility of festivals can bring people together through social media as well."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“I actually hope that after the pandemic, we’ll be able to keep open some of those online slots at festivals that make the festivals more accessible,” Hackett said. “I attended several virtual screenings at Sundance this year, and then after the screening I went on Twitter, and there were filmmakers all over the world who instantly were weighing in with their opinions about the films. That was so exciting to see comments from all over the world, coming from people who might not be able to attend or be able to attend every year.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Dana Reilly, director of the short “Ms. Diva Trucker,” which centers on the experiences of a female long-haul trucker, remarked that Athena has put significant attention to attracting diverse audiences by offering substantial discounts to people who would not otherwise be able to attend. At the same time, she added that film festivals sometimes lose the sense of urgency for viewers to absorb the film’s messages."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“If I publish something online and open it up to the public, people feel as though they can watch it any time; there’s no need to watch it; there’s a lot of competing content on the internet,” Reilly said. “The festival provides … curation and name recognition. People think that there’s something more valuable about this story or a reason that it’s being elevated because it was carefully selected by such a prestigious institution, and the fact that it’s only available for a limited time hopefully, pushes people to take advantage of limited availability.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Similarly, Kate Novack, who produced the short “Hysterical Girl,” which explores Freud’s only major case study of a woman, agreed that Athena has become more accessible with greater viewership and participation while being “thoughtful, reflective of the urgency of the current moment.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Although many filmmakers featured at Athena desperately wish for the return to in-person screenings, many have found a community with other filmmakers and audience members. The past year has halted production schedules, canceled festivals, and isolated film crews, but directors discovered that now more than ever these films—covering everything from disability representation in media to Indigenous rights to advances in STEM—must be seen, whether on a big screen at a drive-in showcase or on a cozy couch at home."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Hopefully when we are post-COVID, or at least mostly vaccinated, we can get on sets again and make magic, because filmmaking really is a team sport. You can't do this alone, and you don't want to,” Fisher said. “It’s really about bringing in all these different skills and talents to create something bigger than what you could do individually.”"
            }
          ],
          "page_1": [
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Amit Lerner, a junior at the School of Visual Arts, prepares her film equipment for a shoot, adjusting the lighting and setting up her video camera. For her new film, she spends much of her time compiling archival footage by sifting through photo albums and documents. But she doesn’t need to go far for the shoot—it’s in her own home, about her own family."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Due to pandemic restrictions, many filmmakers have been unable to direct films or edit footage alongside their usual teams. As a result, these creators have had to completely rethink the storyboarding, filming, and production processes while taking creative risks in order to continue telling stories. For the filmmakers showcasing their projects at the Athena Film Festival, this last year has put a halt to many productions, but it has also pushed them to engage critically with film as a medium to explore and express our current moment."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Lerner, who directed the short film “Pam,” had to quickly adapt to remote learning and production. Living in New York City during the pandemic has limited her ability to film, so for a current project, she chose a subject close to her: her family."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“It’s just trying to be really creative and taking the resources that you have at this moment and [making] something out of it,” Lerner said. “I think that’s a life lesson as well for all students in the future. I think it’s also because [since] it’s more challenging, it’s more rewarding in the end when you’re able to actually make something that you’re proud of.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The student filmmaking experience has certainly posed its challenges, especially when filmmaking requires in-person collaboration on sets and during editing, but Lerner felt that she could branch out and do more creative projects on a lower budget because of the “safety net of our teachers and our peers.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“When you go into the real world, you’re not really going to have what you have in school,” she said. “You’re also going to have to be working with a really, really, really low budget to try and make something and start your career.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Catherine Rafferty, who graduated from the Rochester Institute of Technology in 2020, was able to showcase her film “Hallowed Ground” at her university just a month before the pandemic forced students to leave campus. Her film, which centers on Frederick Douglass’ impact on two Rochester students, meant a lot to viewers who had been advocating for greater racial equity in the Rochester curriculum. The film is also particularly applicable to the lives of students and faculty from the nearby National Technical Institute for the Deaf, since “Hallowed Ground,” alongside other student films, features closed captioning."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The virtual film scene has allowed for films targeting specific audiences such as Rafferty’s to become more mainstream and accessible. But as a first-time filmmaker, missing out on face-to-face interaction has been particularly difficult in terms of incorporating feedback and responses into future projects. However, as a freelancer and a media educator for students in Troy, New York, Rafferty has taken advantage of the pandemic to stay connected and give back to the community she comes from."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“What’s really helped me in the last year is just staying connected to my existing network and really leaning on them during this time, and just trying to maintain those relationships but then also still trying to expand my network online, trying to do more on social media,” Rafferty said. “I think that’s been really important for filmmakers in the last year, really being focused on social media marketing and online distribution.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Making and preserving connections throughout the pandemic has been crucial for Jessica Wolfson, who with Jessie Auritt co-directed “<a href=\"https://watch.athenafilmfestival.com/tv/come-as-you-are-shorts-program/1\">The Paint Wizzard</a>,” a film about an accomplished transgender housepainter. Wolfson, who had to put a number of projects that required flights for shoots on hold during the pandemic, commented that she has had an “amazing year” as a film teacher. Pre-pandemic, her move from New York City to Texas prevented her from teaching at the New York Film Academy. But with the majority of courses being offered remotely, she is now able to continue to teach—both at the Academy and to students in Yemen and across Africa through other film programs."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Because I’m doing everything remotely and everything online, it has actually opened up those opportunities in such an amazing way. I’ve been so grateful that I’ve had these experiences where I got to teach Yemeni students how to direct … and get to know these people that I would never have gotten to know before,” Wolfson said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "The Athena Film Festival has tried to foster such connections between filmmakers as well as give them a platform to not only showcase their films but to educate and converse with their audiences, according to Kory Louko, BC ’17 and postbaccalaureate fellow for the Athena Film Festival. Even though most of the films featured at the festival were filmed and conceived pre-COVID-19, Louko noted that these films had an urgency to them since they touched on themes that were pertinent to current issues of racial unrest, accessibility, and isolation among others."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Part of the festival this year includes a live event with young filmmakers from the Emerging Filmmaker Mentorship Program, a program hosted by the Barnard Sloate Media Center that supports Barnard students in developing and producing their first short films. At this live event, students who had their productions cut short by the onset of COVID-19 discussed their progress as well as the struggles and successes of filmmaking during a pandemic."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "For long-time filmmakers, though, maintaining momentum and adjusting longer projects to meet safety protocols has been “crazy,” Jackie Decker, director of the feature “My Name is Ada Hegerberg,” said. As a filmmaker who specializes in sports productions, Decker noted that the pandemic has completely shifted sports coverage since most games and events still remain closed to teams and select press organizations."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“We did a film for Fox Sports Films that aired last year, where we did conduct interviews but we did them via Zoom. That's a whole new world, and with your camera crew that has to stay far away, there’s all new sorts of ways of getting around filming people by staying socially distant, which was also a huge learning curve for everybody in the industry in that sense,” Decker said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "For a new behind-the-scenes series Decker is currently directing, she has been trying to find inventive ways to navigate protocols such as putting a GoPro in a car to avoid close contact with athletes and the film crew. Normally, Decker would follow an athlete throughout their daily routine, but the team has adapted to capture the lives of athletes and the complexity of the sports world from afar."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Luckily, sports is something that people really wanted to still have, and I think a lot of those leagues knew that and felt that and so the NHL has done a really tremendous job and nothing's been shut down yet,” Decker said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Alongside the sports industry, the dance and theater industries had to quickly pivot to a virtual or socially distanced performance schedule, which has made arts documentaries particularly difficult to conceptualize and shoot. For Liz Sargent, who directed <a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/arts-and-entertainment/2021/03/18/resilience-through-uncertainty-shorts-program-features-stories-of-persistence-and-vulnerability/\">“Strangers’ Reunion,”</a> which was shot and edited prior to the lockdown, the pandemic has been a “really productive” time, especially because her dance background allowed her to document dance as it has evolved over the past year."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“There’s a need in the performing arts to start documenting work in a different way, and also an opportunity to start shooting dance and theater in the more cinematic way,” Sargent said. “So we’ve made several dance films and art films and just finished the series about artists for all arts, so for COVID because we can work in small teams, my husband and I, we’ve actually found this a very productive time.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Many filmmakers have used this time to not only be productive but also rethink the execution and distribution of films. According to Lucy Kennedy, a producer for “<a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/arts-and-entertainment/2021/03/18/the-8th-tells-the-story-of-a-decades-long-fight-for-reproductive-rights-in-ireland/\">The 8th</a>,” the recent consolidation of film distributors has made it more difficult for independent documentary filmmakers to find successful distribution platforms and reach wider audiences. Thus, filmmakers like Kennedy have stressed the importance of public broadcasting, which allows for independent creators to showcase more journalistic or feature projects."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“I think they’re just incredibly important spaces, and they should be really cherished and supported because they don’t have the same commercial imperative that a Netflix or an Apple has, or a Hulu or Amazon,” Kennedy said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Ash Goh Hua, who directed the short “I’m Free Now, You Are Free,” echoed Sargent and Kennedy in that the pandemic pushed them to make films in a “completely different way” that could be more accessible to a larger geographical context. Yet they also cautioned that many films shot and edited remotely may not reach the same standard as in-person films since remote production takes away “the glitz and glamor” of filming with big cameras and a larger budget."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Indeed, COVID-19 has <a href=\"https://www.latimes.com/entertainment-arts/business/story/2020-05-19/coronavirus-raise-costs-movies-productions\">drastically increased</a> filming budgets; enhanced cleaning procedures, additional staff dedicated to taking temperature checks, and implemented social distancing measures can add more than $1 million to a movie budget. Additionally, with staggered shifts for film crews, a short filming process might be extended by multiple weeks and cost thousands of extra dollars per day. Given the changing nature of health protocols and now vaccine distribution, some filmmakers who screened films at the Athena Film Festival have been more cautious about spending money on riskier shoots that might not end up working out."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "According to Loira Limbal, who directed “Through the Night,” COVID-19 completely shifted the entire distribution chain of films, forcing all filmmakers to pivot from traditional film practices and follow their instincts, even when the last year has been “really disorienting and in many ways disempowering.” Limbal, who has still not been able to watch her film with an audience or with her entire crew or protagonists, discovered that she, alongside many other filmmakers, had to roll with the punches as an independent filmmaker not backed by a larger studio."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“You’re already at a disadvantage in the space if you’re an indie filmmaker compared to some films coming out, big studio or is backed by a major platform or sales agent or something, and so the things that you had at your disposal, the tools that you had to kind of get your work out there and build buzz, that all sort of disappeared,” Limbal said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Regina Hoyles, who directed the short film “Adullam,” noted the disparities between larger film studios—which can easily afford these extra COVID-19-related costs—and independent filmmakers, who have faced significant disadvantages over the past year. She noted that many of these independent filmmakers have relied on money raised from platforms like Kickstarter and GoFundMe to finance their projects."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“For the bigger studios, that’s just another drop in the bucket, but for these indie folk who need to have a COVID officer and get these COVID tests scheduled and [have] whole days where actors and crew alike can have their testing, that changes things in terms of finances, which is already a struggle,” Hoyles said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "According to Louko, the Athena Film Festival this year was hyper-aware of financial barriers due to COVID-19. This year, the festival gave out many more submission fee waivers to filmmakers who struggled with fundraising or production costs. Fee waivers were also extended to BIPOC filmmakers who historically—especially during COVID-19—have had few opportunities to submit, let alone showcase, their films at festivals."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Although movie theaters are beginning to open and film crews are starting more in-person productions, Hoyles considered today’s film world as in an “adjustment period” in which people are still actively learning to not only shoot and edit films safely but also reconsider how studios and productions run more broadly."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“How can our unions protect us as creators, as actors, directors, writers, so that we’re not being placed in situations that we really don't have to be in?” she asked. “I guess a lot of us are now realizing, yes, that meeting very much could have been an email, and so in the same way, we're trying to make sure we’re only doing what's necessary.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Beyond just shifts in the filmmaking process, the pandemic has allowed filmmakers to document and uncover facets of society that have gone unnoticed or underreported prior to the pandemic. The film community, in addition to creating films about current events, has held many people in power accountable for upholding racist structures, whether it be unequal pay or silencing certain narratives."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“A lot of what we’re seeing now is nothing new, it's just getting recorded,” Hoyles said. “So it was really interesting to see everyone have nothing to do and have no choice but to look at themselves, look at themselves on a personal level, look at themselves on a relational level with whoever they’re close to, and then look at the world and look at themselves and where they fit in and line up in terms of, am I on the right side of history?”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Similarly, Rayna Zemel, a producer for  a short film about the George Floyd protests titled “We Can’t Breathe,” said that filmmakers especially tried to dismantle not only white supremacy but also the misinformationthat people are taught that reinforce racist policies. Through her film, for example, she was able to showcase a side of the protests that was often obscured or not covered by the media."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“Focusing on a narrative that makes [the protests] more personal I feel helps people to see that they are actually people with motivations and fears and hopes and joys and it's not just angry mobs looting and destroying property. These are actually people that have backstories and whatnot,” Zemel said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Hua’s “I’m Free Now, You Are Free” depicted the reunion between Mike Africa Jr. and Debbie Africa, a formerly incarcerated political prisoner of the MOVE 9 who was arrested after an attack by the Philadelphia Police Department. According to Hua, the pandemic opened “fissures of possibilities for people to see things in different ways,” such as the realities of the United States prison system."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“People are starting to see how prisons are really like festering grounds—I mean, they were never healthy to begin with—but now you can really see the capacity of death for a lot more people,” Hua said. “And I think that opened a lot more people up to the concept of abolition, for example.”"
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Given the complexity of this past year, the Athena Film Festival worked to advance these nuanced conversations and bring awareness to issues like disability representation in film, white supremacy, access to health care, and female representation in the sciences. With nine shorts programs, the festival has widened the scope of coverage and has given female and nonbinary filmmakers a chance to comment and reflect on the current landscape."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "“You have all of these films that at first have nothing to do with each other, and then you put them in a program and they start to talk to each other, and they create something new,” Louko said."
            },
            {
              "type": "text",
              "value": "Despite major setbacks to the industry that include growing funding disparities, limited resources in a remote environment, and restricted subjects to cover in sports and the arts, filmmakers have used their creativity and passion for the art form to continue telling pressing and heartfelt narratives, whether on the protest lines or from the comfort of their own homes."
            },
            {
              "type": "page_2",
              "value": [
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "Lesley Elizondo spends most of her days directing, writing, and teaching about films. When not working on independent projects, she leads cinematography courses at the New York Film Academy and the University of California, Los Angeles, instructing students in motion picture camera preparation, composition, framing, and lighting."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "Elizondo produced and did the cinematography for “Basta,” a film featured at this year’s Athena Film Festival. Viewers praised her for chronicling the efforts of the Ya Basta Coalition, a group created by female night janitors that survived sexual abuse at the workplace whose name means “enough is enough.”"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "As a Mexican American filmmaker, Elizondo noted that she cannot rely solely on independent filmmaking as a career despite the acclaim her films receive."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "“No one has come out and hired me and given me a sustainable wage for a project that can kind of keep me going on to the next project to the next project,” Elizondo said. “Obviously, right now with COVID a lot of productions have just kind of shut down, but even before that, being a brown woman who is a cinematographer who doesn’t come with her own equipment, it's next to impossible to get hired into production.”"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "For many of the filmmakers at the Athena Film Festival, the path to showing their films on viewers’ laptops was filled with systemic obstacles. But even now that these filmmakers have shown their films at dozens of domestic and international festivals, the future of women and nonbinary creators remains unclear as they struggle to make ends meet doing what they love."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "According to a <a href=\"https://womenintvfilm.sdsu.edu/wp-content/uploads/2021/01/2020_Celluloid_Ceiling_Report.pdf\">2020 “Celluloid Ceiling” report</a>, “women comprised 21 percent of all directors, writers, producers, executive producers, editors, and cinematographers working on the top 100 grossing films in 2020, up from 20 percent in 2019.” The industry has made significant progress toward empowering women directors, since women accounted for 16 percent of directors working on the top 100 grossing films in 2020, compared to a mere 4 percent in 2018."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "For films included on the Digital Entertainment Group’s “Watched at Home” list from March through December 2020, however, women comprise just 9 percent of directors and 15 percent of executive producers. Despite the upward trend in the number of women directors over the past three years, 67 percent of films in 2020 employed zero to four women in the aforementioned roles, whereas only 9 percent employed 10 or more women. In contrast, 5 percent of films employed zero to four men, while 71 percent employed 10 or more men."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "These statistics can be explained in part by the gender pay gap that still exists both at Hollywood studios and much smaller production companies. <a href=\"https://www.theguardian.com/world/2019/sep/15/hollywoods-gender-pay-gap-revealed-male-stars-earn-1m-more-per-film-than-women\">In Hollywood</a>, for example, male stars made $1.1 million more per film than women. <a href=\"https://www.workingideal.com/wp-content/uploads/2018/06/Secretaries-Script-Girls-and-Stereotypes.pdf\">Script supervisors</a>, about 90 percent of whom are women, make roughly half the weekly earnings of first assistant directors, 77 percent of which are men."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "According to Samantha Knowles, director of “Tangled Roots,” the inaccessibility of the film industry goes beyond just hiring women and gender-nonconforming people. Both Knowles and Elizondo believe that unfair and unequal salaries prevent filmmakers from working in the industry in the first place. Those who can afford to stay in the industry rarely receive promotions and thus higher salaries, a phenomenon that keeps women in positions like writer’s assistants rather than producers or directors. Knowles posits that the industry will become more accessible and diverse when filmmakers of color trying to fix systemic issues in the industry receive the recognition they deserve."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "“I know so many people … who are hired at the entry level, and then they don’t stay because it’s not sustainable, they’re not paid fairly or they’re not paid at all, so they can’t afford to stay in the industry,” Knowles said. “So I really feel like people need to put their money where their mouth is, and they need to actually pay people fairly and then actually promote them and pave the path to somebody being a director or being a capital ‘P’ producer or being in the writers’ room.”"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "Women just getting their start in the film industry may become discouraged by the lack of female representation in positions of power. According to Jen Rainin, co-director of the documentary “Ahead of the Curve,” young female filmmakers need to be “able to see it to be it,” and when women rarely occupy executive roles in films, student filmmakers may reconsider their decision to pursue film."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "To Rainin, this lack of representation goes beyond dissuading young filmmakers from becoming independent filmmakers. The straight white men who typically already occupy executive positions tend to hire others like themselves to fill higher-ranking job openings, especially on projects with large budgets.“Because there are so few and there are even fewer in a position at studios to greenlight projects, because we’re talking with the film world about usually fairly large budgets, large dollar amounts, because of human nature, we tend to trust people who look like us with larger amounts of money before we go out of our comfort zone,” Rainin said."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "This phenomenon results in a real drop-off of the number of women filmmakers who make a second or third feature—an issue that rarely occurs among men. According to Rainin, male directors who win awards at festivals like Sundance are more likely to be given a multi-million dollar feature deal than female directors."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "Rainin and co-director Rivkah Beth Medow specifically put together an all-women crew with many queer women for “Ahead of the Curve,” a film about Franco Stevens’ launch of “Curve,” the best-selling lesbian magazine ever published. Rainin and Medow wanted to widen the opportunities for women filmmakers and create a mentorship model that would help prepare less-experienced filmmakers for directing their own feature-length documentaries."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "“Even though we knew it might take a little longer, and we might end up paying a little bit more for that or having longer days, it’s so important to create those pathways to professional experience for women and to take a chance on women,” Medow said. “The only reason that we’re not in those positions just as much is just because it’s not for lack of talent, it’s not for lack of passion, it’s not for lack of hunger, it’s just lack of opportunity.”"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "This opportunity for women and queer filmmakers to play an active role in producing a documentary means considerably more when taking into account the highly competitive nature of the industry. According to Jalena Keane-Lee, director of “Standing Above the Clouds,” the fight for funding is fierce, with some fellowships having to narrow down over 600 films to just three."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "“In addition, there’s not that many resources available with a quick turnaround,” Keane-Lee said. “So even if you do get funded, it might be eight months from when you applied with a project that could be really urgent, because usually [funding programs] want things that are urgent.”"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "For Jessica Earnshaw, the director of “<a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/arts-and-entertainment/2021/03/17/jessica-earnshaw-tells-a-story-of-love-generations-and-family-in-jacinta/\">Jacinta</a>,” the funding process can be really difficult to navigate. Earnshaw shot “Jacinta” mostly using out-of-pocket earnings from her photography projects, noting that the cost of making films locks a lot of people out of the industry."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "The difficulty in securing funding stems from the fact that the arts are criminally underfunded. The 2021 New York City budget <a href=\"https://news.artnet.com/art-world/nyc-slashes-art-education-budget-1891325\">slashed funding</a> for public school arts education by 70 percent, thereby reducing the funds from $21.5 million to a mere $6.5 million. As a result of budget cuts such as this, Loira Limbal, director of “<a href=\"https://www.columbiaspectator.com/arts-and-entertainment/2021/03/23/athena-film-festivals-through-the-night-offers-an-ode-to-working-women-and-caregivers/\">Through the Night</a>,” views the art world as a “space of the elite” in which only the wealthy can make a career out of filmmaking."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "“So much of access relies on what relationships, what networks you are a part of, and if you don't come from a background where your parents or someone else has paved the way, it can be virtually impossible to figure out a way in, and nothing really in the U.S. is a meritocracy,” Limbal said."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "Ashley O’Shay, director of a film titled “Unapologetic” that is about two fierce abolitionist leaders in Chicago, further explained that prohibitive costs and hard-to-find funding particularly disadvantages first-time Black filmmakers. O’Shay did not get funding until three and a half years into the filming process, attributing this in part to her relative inexperience at the time she began filming."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "“I think there’s already a built-in barrier for a lot of first-time filmmakers when it comes to approaching institutions and grant-makers because there’s not a lot of faith, or there’s a bar that is set that you have to prove that you know how to make a film, that you know how to complete a feature-length film,” O’Shay said."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "When taking a more intersectional approach, however, O’Shay noted that those in control of funding films made by Black women about Black women may not understand the necessity of stories like these. In her case, she thought that funders may have wanted to see a film on the spectacle of the <a href=\"https://m4bl.org/ \">Movement for Black Lives in Chicago</a> instead of the more intimate, personalized angle she took."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "“I really wanted to still make sure that I was always existing or like presenting myself authentically in [the film],” O’Shay said. “Subconsciously, just because [of] who the dominant identity and personality is in the film industry, it was definitely something personally I had to push myself on because we all deal with wanting people to like you, wanting people to like you so they could give you money or support.”"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "For many women of color on the executive side of production, similar challenges arise in that the burden of giving a voice to other women of color falls on them, according to Ellie Wen, who directed a film titled “The Missfits” that is centered on a women’s robotics team. She noted that she experienced the most sexism while working in Hollywood production companies in part because she had to spearhead efforts to document underrepresented communities. Even so, she remains optimistic that such issues are trending in the right direction after a recent reckoning in the industry in response to the protests of the summer. The representation of women in STEM, however, still remains minimal."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "“I still think that there’s a long way to go in terms of representation, especially in the narrative film space,” Wen said. “It’s just baffling to me how few stories there still are about female scientists or doctors, it still is like a handful that people can probably count.”"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "Challenges surrounding funding also disadvantage filmmakers with disabilities like Ashley Eakin, the director of “Single,” who has a rare bone condition. Eakin previously worked on “Crazy Rich Asians” with director Jon Chu, who gave her a shot to prove herself on set."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "“I think one of the big things is fear that holds people back because they don’t know how to navigate talking with a disabled person if they are unable to do something,” Eakin said. “That doesn’t mean that every disabled person is unable to do everything but … I guess the bigger question is why being unable to do certain things is that inherently negative.”"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "For her short film “Single,” in which a girl born with one arm is set up with a guy missing a hand, Eakin cast two filmmakers with disabilities as the main characters. Eakin had a difficult time finding actors who had limb disabilities, acknowledging that the two leads did not have a ton of acting experience. Eakin also noted that often a director with a limited budget or filming window would rather rely on veteran actors."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "“I think that maybe it’s the fear of trying to get a good performance out of someone is why they don’t go with these people, and then I also think it’s because of the financiers saying they need a big name; they need someone fancy to be in this role,” Eakin said. “It has to be that disabled actors are getting the roles because they can never play non-disabled roles, and so they should be the ones who are getting hired for that.”"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "With such a small pool of actors that can play the roles Eakin writes, she admitted that taking on less experienced actors with disabilities is a risky “trial and error process” of navigating the strategies for newer actors’ best performances. This conversation also applies to people without disabilities; echoing Rainin, Eakin believes that executives are often fearful of hiring younger filmmakers and actors who may be unable to perform certain tasks."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "Nevertheless, many filmmakers showcasing films at the Athena Film Festival acknowledged that film companies and executives are trying to fix issues of funding, accessibility, racial bias, and disability advocacy within the industry. According to Italian American director Cecilia Albertini, CC ’13, who co-directed “Basta” with Elizondo, there is an increased awareness of the fact that women are not given as much of a voice as men. Italy, for example, is 20 years behind when it comes to women in film."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "Albertini cites the success of women at the 2021 Golden Globes as a sign of progress in the industry, from Chloé Zhao winning Best Director for “Nomadland” to Andra Day winning Best Performance in a Motion Picture Drama."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "With funding assistance from major organizations and fee waivers for applications to film festivals, filmmakers can worry less about the potential risks of going against their conscience by creating a film that differs from their artistic vision in order to accommodate fiscal concerns. Rainin noted that as barriers to entry continue to be broken down, such as with the Athena Film Festival accepting dozens of feature and short films from filmmakers of all backgrounds, more nuanced and unheard stories are being brought to the big screens."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "“The stories that are told about the way that queer women are portrayed in media, they’re often being told by straight men or straight women, not by us, and we have a different lens. We see our stories through a particular lens,” Rainin said. “I think that is one of the things that Athena is getting at, our film is explicitly about visibility, queer women’s visibility.”"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "For Eakin, as visibility of disability movements grows, more young filmmakers with disabilities who were told that they had no career in film will enter the industry and be able to tell their stories."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "“I was just super honest in the film, and I think that’s something that sometimes … for me at least, I would try and compensate so people would like me, I would never rock the boat, I would never be too blunt, even though I naturally kind of can be sometimes, or very outspoken which, as a director, you have to be,” Eakin said. “But I really just leaned into like the honesty and the truth of what I was dealing with, with internalized ableism.”"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "O’Shay has seen film studios and production companies over the past few months internally interrogate how they are—or are not—centering Black experiences and healthily engaging with Black people both on staff and the communities they film. She noticed that a lot of white executives have taken a step back and refer to other people for certain projects who would be a better fit to tell those stories."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "“I don’t think this film would have looked the same way if a white woman or a man was the one in the director’s chair. I was very aware of that because I wanted the film to feel like it was made by a young Black woman,” O’Shay said. “I think a lot of the positive feedback that we’ve been seeing and how people respond to different moments in the film is a result of that decision.”"
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "When women filmmakers have greater opportunities to showcase the communities with which they are familiar, perspectives rarely seen in mainstream media can become amplified, as seen with the women of Turkana County, Kenya, who are shown in Anjali Nayar’s film “Oil & Water.” Nayar, who served as a foreign correspondent based in Nairobi for Reuters, read reports about oil expansion in the region and decided to showcase how the women of the community, who had never had any say in land rights, rallied together against patriarchal systems and corrupt politics to protect their futures."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "For her, film is about nurturing diverse perspectives without having one dominating narrative showcased at festivals. Although barriers to entry still keep women and minority filmmakers out of many film spaces, festivals like the Athena Film Festival are centering marginalized voices, reexamining who can tell stories, who can play certain roles, and who can break down the barriers that make the film world an elite and inaccessible space."
                },
                {
                  "type": "text",
                  "value": "“Everybody has a story, everybody has an experience, and as an audience what often feels most surprising and interesting and different and beautiful is something that you haven’t seen before, so making sure that the voices [are] not just a specific and controlling voice is really important,” Nayar said."
                }
              ]
            }
          ]
